        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 29. 78</date>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Evans,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I think you are doing a very great service to Natural Science by getting the caves of Borneo explored. I shall be happy to subscribe £20, but I do not send a cheque as if more is necessary I shall be glad to give £30 or £40.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I wish some one as energetic as yourself would organise an expedition to the triassic lacustrine beds in S: Africa, where the cliffs are said to be almost composed of bones.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Pray believe me yours very sincerely, | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD sent a cheque for £20 on 2 September 1878 (CD’s Classed account books (Down House MS)). On the expedition to explore caves in Borneo, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11337.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Evans, 28 January 1878</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The Triassic lacustrine deposits of South Africa were a rich source of reptilian fossils, intermediate forms important for the history of evolution (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1974.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">A. Desmond 1982</ref>, pp. 195–9).  <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3629.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Richard Owen</ref> had written of ‘the singular and suggestive concordance of dentition with that in carnivorous mammals’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9662.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">R. Owen 1876</ref>, p. 29).</note>
        </div>
    
